ve"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfcpex"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">C&amp;E Executive News Filter</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gsecbr"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="niwe"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">IWE Filter</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:nnam"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">ST</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Facebook runs UK, US newspaper ads apologising for data scandal</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>LONDON (AFP, REUTERS) - Facebook chief Mark Zuckerberg took out full-page ads in nine major British and US newspapers on Sunday (March 25) to apologise for a huge data privacy scandal.</Para><Para>"We have a responsibility to protect your information. If we can't we don't deserve it," he said.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>The ads ran in prominent positions in six British nationals, including the best-selling Mail on Sunday, The Sunday Times and The Observer .Çô which helped break the story .Çô as well as the New York Times, Washington Post and the Wall Street Journal.</Para><Para>The world's largest social media network is facing growing government scrutiny in Europe and the United States.</Para><Para>This follows allegations by a whistleblower that British consultancy Cambridge Analytica improperly accessed users'information to build profiles on American voters that were later used to help elect US President Donald Trump in 2016.</Para><Para>The plain black text apology on a white background, with only a tiny Facebook logo, appeared in Sunday publications including The Observer - one of the newspapers whose reporting on the issue has sent Facebook's share price tumbling.</Para><Para>Zuckerberg said an app built by a university researcher"leaked Facebook data of millions of people in 2014".</Para><Para>"This was a breach of trust, and I'm sorry we didn't do more at the time," Zuckerberg said, reiterating an apology first made last week in US television interviews.</Para><Para>Cambridge Analytica says it initially believed the data had been obtained in line with data protection laws, and later deleted it at Facebook's request.</Para><Para>The consultancy said it did not use the data in work it did for the 2016 US election.</Para><Para>On Friday night, investigators from Britain's data watchdog searched the London offices of Cambridge Analytica for several hours.</Para><Para>Zuckerberg, whose firm has lost more than US$50 billion (S$66 billion) in market value since the allegations, said Facebook would give users more information and control about who can access their data.</Para><Para>"Thank you for believing in this community. I promise to do better for you," he wrote.</Para><Para>Advertisers Mozilla and German bank Commerzbank have suspended ads on the service and the hashtag #DeleteFacebook has been trending online.</Para><Para>On Friday, electric carmaker Tesla Inc and its rocket company SpaceX's Facebook pages - each with more than 2.6 million followers - were deleted after Chief Executive Elon Musk promised to do so. Related Stories: walden_cambridgeanalytica_230318.jpg Related StoryIndia queries Cambridge Analytica over alleged Facebook data breach 2018-03-23t131601z_783951980_rc1610c889b0_rtrmadp_3_facebook-cambridge-analytica-zuckerberg.jpg Related StoryFacebook crisis prompts Silicon Valley soul-searching nz_bolton_24_0.jpg Related StoryJohn Bolton was early beneficiary of Cambridge Analytica's Facebook data nz_britain01_24.jpg Related StoryBritish investigators enter London office of firm at centre of Facebook data storm nm-ca-2403.jpg Related StoryCambridge Analytica's real business isn't data bp_sheryl_sandberg_230318_43.jpg Related StoryFacebook chief operating officer Sheryl Sandberg says she regrets not speaking out sooner nz_stocks_23.jpg Related StoryWhat's ailing tech? Investors are not waiting to find out nz_fb_22.jpg Related StoryFacebook scandal could push other tech companies to tighten data sharing Zuckerberg promises changes after data scandal Related StoryMark Zuckerberg's response to data scandal doesn't 'cut it', Facebook's critics say Zuckerberg promises changes after data scandal Related StoryMark Zuckerberg admits Facebook made mistakes on user data nz_germany_22.jpg Related StoryGermany summons Facebook over user data safety concerns: Report wl_fbscandal_210318.jpg Related StoryTimeline of Facebook, Cambridge Analytica scandal dw-cambridgeanalytica-180321.jpg Related StoryKey players in the Facebook, Cambridge Analytica data scandal yq_cw_20.jpg Related StoryChristopher Wylie: The whistleblower in the Cambridge Analytica scandal bp_facebook_200318_38.jpg Related StoryFacebook suspends Trump-linked firm</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field"></Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

